[Event "Baker Bridge - Elimination Plays"]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "1"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "S:Q5.AJ62.A964.AJ5 K863.Q983.T75.82 A4.5.KJ3.KQT9643 JT972.KT74.Q82.7"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "6C"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "S"]
1NT pass 3C pass 4C pass 6C pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 1, chOption: N, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:0, nBasis: 2, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "ae89ac2ff54bece0214fc0b45f06e5d1c583a46c4df8d2c8b91e79179c3f45e8"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/elimination_plays"]
[Student "S"]
{North considered Blackwood, then realized if South showed either 2 or 3 Aces he was going to bid slam. But if South showed just one Ace he would have to maneuver to play 5NT which might be worse than 6\C. So he just bid the slam. North plays 6\C. East leads the \SJ.

You wish, you hope, you may even pray, but when you play the \SQ West covers with the \SK. So you know you have a \S loser. And unless West holds the \DQ you might have a \D loser also.

Perhaps an elimination play will improve your chances. Don't lead a trump yet though, you're going to need several entries to dummy to eliminate the \Hs. 

Win the \S, play to the \HA and ruff a \H.

Play a trump to dummy's \CJ (both defenders follow) and ruff another \H high.

Play to dummy's \CA, pulling their last trump, and ruff the last \H.

Now execute the throw-in by leading a \S. If East wins the trick he will have to play \Ds for you or give you a ruff-sluff. So if these are competent defenders they will make sure that it is <b>WEST</b> who wins the \S trick. So he does, and he plays a small \D.

<b>DO NOT PLAY THE JACK!</b> If the finesse is going to work now it will still work one trick later. By playing low you take advantage of the possibility that West held the \D10 and East will have to put on the \DQ to prevent you taking a trick with dummy's \D9.

Many elimination endings give you a sure thing. Others just improve your chances.  

Here you had two chances. First, East might have HAD to win the throw-in, either because he had all of the high \Ss, or more likely because he messed up. The second chance paid off when West took the throw-in but you found a fortunate position with the \Ds.}
[Play "W"]SJ

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:KJ8.AJ5.A3.AJT72 965.9843.KQT52.6 AT72.KQ.984.KQ84 Q43.T762.J76.953"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "6C"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1C pass 1S pass 2NT pass 4C pass 6C pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "6bb7b8475000c23132f03a8c88d4600eb427a9869f3d9ac561cb340be6f49153"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/elimination_plays"]
[Student "S"]
{The slam was easy to bid, now you just have to make it. East plays 6\C. South leads the \DQ.

You have one certain \D loser, and a two-way finesse for the \SQ. That should make you start thinking about elimination and throw-in. So win the \DA and pull trumps, South having a singleton.

Now eliminate \Hs from your hand and dummy by playing \HK, \HA, \HJ.<b>BUT BE CAREFUL!</b> On the \HJ you must discard a \D from dummy so both of you will be out of \Ds at the throw-in.

<b>NOW</b> you can execute the throw-in. Play your \D, which eliminates \Ds from both you and dummy and at the same time throws in one of the defenders. Whoever it is will be forced to lead a \S and eliminate your guess for the \SQ or else give you a ruff-sluff, allowing you to ruff in dummy and discard a \S loser from your hand.

Among Bridge players you often hear about someone (usually Aunt Harriet) who is amazingly lucky at guessing the location of missing Queens.  

Perhaps Aunt Harriet isn't that lucky after all, perhaps she just knows how to perform elimination plays.

Hopefully in the future you will be the one with the reputation!}
[Play "W"]DQ

